Analyzing the Evolution of NBA Game Scores and Three-Point Shooting Trends Over Time¶

Vinay Gundu, Contribution 100%

Introduction¶

NBA games are seeing record-breaking scores, with results like 125:130 or halftime scores of 70:75, which used to resemble full-game scores in the past. To verify this, I want to analyze historical data to determine if scoring growth has been consistent and linear over the years. Additionally, there's a perception that basketball has shifted towards prioritizing three-point shooting, possibly influenced by players like Stephen Curry. It's important to investigate whether there's been an increase in the number of three-point attempts and successes over time, and see how the game has evolved over time.

Data Curation¶

The dataset I will be using is this https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/wyattowalsh/basketball?resource=download. This dataset includes 65,000+ games (every game since the inaugural 1946-47 NBA season) and Box Scores for over 95% of all games. These are very useful for my project so I can isolate point totals in games, as well as 3 pointers made in a single game, which I can use to investigate the trends aforementioned. Specifically, I worked with the game.csv file.

Wow, a very clear trend is apparent. We can see a very positive relationship as the years have gone on in correlation with the number of 3-point shots made. For context, the average of 25 3-pointers made per game provides valuable insight into the prevalence and significance of long-range shooting in NBA gameplay. Given that each successful 3-pointer adds three points to a team's score, totaling 75 points for all 25 shots. In the context of 3-point shooting dynamics, the average of 25 3-pointers made per game in contemporary NBA games starkly contrasts with the landscape of the early 90s and 80s. During those eras, the total number of 3-pointers made per game typically ranged between 0 and 5. This significant shift over time reflects the evolution of basketball strategy and the increasing emphasis on long-range shooting as a fundamental aspect of offensive gameplay.

One Sample T-Test¶

I want to do a one-sample t-test comparing the mean total scores for all years against a specific value. This can help determine if the mean total scores are significantly different from a particular benchmark or expectation. I have chosen a benchmark of 200. I chose 200 as a benchmark for total scores in NBA games because it represents a commonly observed threshold signifying a moderately high-scoring game, providing a meaningful point of comparison for evaluating scoring trends and deviations from typical scoring norms.

Null Hypothesis (H0): The mean total score for all years is 200.

Alternative Hypothesis (HA): The mean total score for all years is greater than 200.

In [ ]:
from scipy.stats import ttest_1samp


benchmark_value = 200


t_stat, p_value = ttest_1samp(df_years, benchmark_value)

alpha = 0.05

print("One-Sample t-test Results:")
print("Test Statistic (t-value):", t_stat)
print("P-value:", p_value)

One-Sample t-test Results:
Test Statistic (t-value): 1.754243484355025
P-value: 0.08341971410683675

Since the P-value of 0.083 is greater than our alpha value of 0.05 we fail to reject the null hypothesis. There is no significant evidence to conclude that the mean total score for all years is significantly greater than 200

Primary Analysis and Visualization¶

We initiate the process by leveraging seasonal decomposition from the statsmodels library to deconstruct the total points' time series into its constituent elements—trend, seasonal, and residual patterns. This enables us to uncover the underlying dynamics and fluctuations in NBA game scores, offering profound insights into the temporal trends shaping the basketball landscape.

Following this, we transition into predictive modeling, where we use linear regression to forecast total points based on the number of three-pointers made per game. After preparing the data and splitting it into training and testing sets, we train the regression model to capture the relationship between three-point shooting proficiency and overall game scores. By evaluating the model's performance using mean squared error and looking its coefficients and intercept, we gain invaluable insights into the predictive capabilities of our model and the factors influencing game outcomes.

Looking towards the future, we extend our analysis to make predictions for forthcoming dates in 2025, assuming different values for the number of three-pointers made per game. This forward-looking approach allows us to anticipate potential game outcomes and envisage the impact of varying three-point shooting performances on total points scored. Furthermore, we assess our model's historical predictive prowess by forecasting total points per game for past dates and comparing the predicted values with actual outcomes, providing a comprehensive evaluation of the model's accuracy and efficacy.

In [ ]:
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from statsmodels.tsa.seasonal import seasonal_decompose
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error
from sklearn.impute import SimpleImputer


decomposition = seasonal_decompose(df['total_points'], model='additive', period=365)
trend = decomposition.trend
seasonal = decomposition.seasonal
residual = decomposition.resid

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))
plt.subplot(411)
plt.plot(df['game_date'], df['total_points'], label='Original')
plt.legend(loc='upper left')
plt.subplot(412)
plt.plot(df['game_date'], trend, label='Trend')
plt.legend(loc='upper left')
plt.subplot(413)
plt.plot(df['game_date'], seasonal, label='Seasonal')
plt.legend(loc='upper left')
plt.subplot(414)
plt.plot(df['game_date'], residual, label='Residual')
plt.legend(loc='upper left')
plt.tight_layout()


X = df[['3_pointers_made']]
y = df['total_points']


imputer = SimpleImputer(strategy='mean')
X_imputed = imputer.fit_transform(X)

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X_imputed, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)

regression_model = LinearRegression()
regression_model.fit(X_train, y_train)


y_pred = regression_model.predict(X_test)

mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred)
print(f"Mean Squared Error: {mse}")


coefficients = regression_model.coef_
intercept = regression_model.intercept_
print(f"Coefficients: {coefficients}")
print(f"Intercept: {intercept}")


three_pointers_values = [20, 25, 30, 35, 40]

for value in three_pointers_values:
    future_dates = pd.date_range(start='2025-01-01', end='2025-01-05', freq='D')
    future_data = pd.DataFrame({'3_pointers_made': [value] * len(future_dates)}, index=future_dates)
    future_predictions = regression_model.predict(imputer.transform(future_data[['3_pointers_made']]))

    print(f"Future Predictions for 3-Pointers Made = {value}:")
    print(future_predictions)



past_predictions = regression_model.predict(X_imputed)

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.plot(df['game_date'], df['total_points'], label='Actual', color='blue')
plt.plot(df['game_date'], past_predictions, label='Predicted (Historical)', linestyle='--', color='green')
plt.xlabel('Date')
plt.ylabel('Total Points')
plt.title('Actual vs Predicted Total Points per NBA Game (Historical Dates)')
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

The predictions consistently hovering around the low 200's range suggest that our model may not capture the full variability and complexity of the total points scored in NBA games over time. This could be attributed to several factors, such as the simplicity of our linear regression model, which may not adequately capture non-linear relationships and other underlying factors influencing game scores. This makes sense because the Mean Squared Error (MSE) of approximately 639.64 is pretty high, suggesting that our model's predictions deviate significantly from the actual total points scored in NBA games.

Conclusions¶

Based on the comprehensive analysis of historical NBA game data, several key insights have emerged regarding scoring trends and the evolution of three-point shooting in basketball.

Firstly, the analysis revealed a notable increase in total points scored in NBA games over time, with recent games featuring record-breaking scores that surpass previous norms. This trend underscores a significant shift in the dynamics of basketball gameplay, with teams achieving higher scoring outputs than in the past.

Moreover, the data analysis confirmed the perception that basketball has increasingly prioritized three-point shooting, with a substantial rise in both the number of three-point attempts and successes observed over the years. This trend aligns with the broader strategic emphasis on long-range shooting in modern basketball, influenced in part by elite players like Stephen Curry, who have revolutionized the game with their prolific three-point shooting.

Overall, the findings from the data analysis suggest a clear evolution in the style and strategy of NBA basketball, characterized by higher scoring games and a greater reliance on three-point shooting. These insights provide valuable context for understanding the changing dynamics of the sport and offer actionable insights for teams, coaches, and analysts seeking to optimize their strategies and performance in the modern basketball landscape.

Options
=======
The options below are convenience aliases to configurable class-options,
as listed in the "Equivalent to" description-line of the aliases.
To see all configurable class-options for some <cmd>, use:
    <cmd> --help-all

--debug
    set log level to logging.DEBUG (maximize logging output)
    Equivalent to: [--Application.log_level=10]
--show-config
    Show the application's configuration (human-readable format)
    Equivalent to: [--Application.show_config=True]
--show-config-json
    Show the application's configuration (json format)
    Equivalent to: [--Application.show_config_json=True]
--generate-config
    generate default config file
    Equivalent to: [--JupyterApp.generate_config=True]
-y
    Answer yes to any questions instead of prompting.
    Equivalent to: [--JupyterApp.answer_yes=True]
--execute
    Execute the notebook prior to export.
    Equivalent to: [--ExecutePreprocessor.enabled=True]
--allow-errors
    Continue notebook execution even if one of the cells throws an error and include the error message in the cell output (the default behaviour is to abort conversion). This flag is only relevant if '--execute' was specified, too.
    Equivalent to: [--ExecutePreprocessor.allow_errors=True]
--stdin
    read a single notebook file from stdin. Write the resulting notebook with default basename 'notebook.*'
    Equivalent to: [--NbConvertApp.from_stdin=True]
--stdout
    Write notebook output to stdout instead of files.
    Equivalent to: [--NbConvertApp.writer_class=StdoutWriter]
--inplace
    Run nbconvert in place, overwriting the existing notebook (only
            relevant when converting to notebook format)
    Equivalent to: [--NbConvertApp.use_output_suffix=False --NbConvertApp.export_format=notebook --FilesWriter.build_directory=]
--clear-output
    Clear output of current file and save in place,
            overwriting the existing notebook.
    Equivalent to: [--NbConvertApp.use_output_suffix=False --NbConvertApp.export_format=notebook --FilesWriter.build_directory= --ClearOutputPreprocessor.enabled=True]
--no-prompt
    Exclude input and output prompts from converted document.
    Equivalent to: [--TemplateExporter.exclude_input_prompt=True --TemplateExporter.exclude_output_prompt=True]
--no-input
    Exclude input cells and output prompts from converted document.
            This mode is ideal for generating code-free reports.
    Equivalent to: [--TemplateExporter.exclude_output_prompt=True --TemplateExporter.exclude_input=True --TemplateExporter.exclude_input_prompt=True]
--allow-chromium-download
    Whether to allow downloading chromium if no suitable version is found on the system.
    Equivalent to: [--WebPDFExporter.allow_chromium_download=True]
--disable-chromium-sandbox
    Disable chromium security sandbox when converting to PDF..
    Equivalent to: [--WebPDFExporter.disable_sandbox=True]
--show-input
    Shows code input. This flag is only useful for dejavu users.
    Equivalent to: [--TemplateExporter.exclude_input=False]
--embed-images
    Embed the images as base64 dataurls in the output. This flag is only useful for the HTML/WebPDF/Slides exports.
    Equivalent to: [--HTMLExporter.embed_images=True]
--sanitize-html
    Whether the HTML in Markdown cells and cell outputs should be sanitized..
    Equivalent to: [--HTMLExporter.sanitize_html=True]

    Equivalent to: [--Application.log_level]

    Whether the HTML in Markdown cells and cell outputs should be sanitized.This

--reveal-prefix=<Unicode>
    The URL prefix for reveal.js (version 3.x).

            If a relative path is given, it must be a subdirectory of the

    Equivalent to: [--NotebookExporter.nbformat_version]

Examples
--------

    The simplest way to use nbconvert is

            > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb --to html

            Options include ['asciidoc', 'custom', 'html', 'latex', 'markdown', 'notebook', 'pdf', 'python', 'rst', 'script', 'slides', 'webpdf'].

            > jupyter nbconvert --to latex mynotebook.ipynb

            Both HTML and LaTeX support multiple output templates. LaTeX includes
            'base', 'article' and 'report'.  HTML includes 'basic', 'lab' and
            'classic'. You can specify the flavor of the format used.

            > jupyter nbconvert --to html --template lab mynotebook.ipynb

            You can also pipe the output to stdout, rather than a file

            > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb --stdout

            PDF is generated via latex

            > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb --to pdf

            You can get (and serve) a Reveal.js-powered slideshow

            > jupyter nbconvert myslides.ipynb --to slides --post serve

            Multiple notebooks can be given at the command line in a couple of
            different ways:

            > jupyter nbconvert notebook*.ipynb
            > jupyter nbconvert notebook1.ipynb notebook2.ipynb

            or you can specify the notebooks list in a config file, containing::

                c.NbConvertApp.notebooks = ["my_notebook.ipynb"]

            > jupyter nbconvert --config mycfg.py

To see all available configurables, use `--help-all`.
